page.title: 07FLORA
page.content: There is a vast abundance of plant life in the area, with large expanses of green meadow. A survey was carried out to examine the flora, in a square metre. This was performed in three different locations, in a field, by the roadside and on the grass verge by the seashore. In square one, in the field, there were many different types of grasses. Plantain and Dover were very common, with birds-eye speedwell playing a less important role. No other plants could be seen. In the second square, which was positioned by the road side, a number of colourful plants could be identified among the grass. These included a patch of Vetch, Pink Campion, Daisies, buttercups and Yarrow. The third square was positioned on a grassy verge on the coast road, The grass in this square was much coarser.
